CALENDAR (03): PRIMARY AMEBIC MENINGOENCEPHALITIS SUMMIT - USA: 11 SEP 2015
********************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: 4 Sep 2015
From: Jack Tracy <Jack.Tracy@flhealth.gov> [edited]


Upcoming Primary Amebic Meningoencephalitis/Amoeba Summit - Orlando Florida USA, 11 Sep 2015, 7:30am - 2:30pm
http://www.idsociety.org/uploadedFiles/IDSA/Meetings/Calendar/Amoeba%20Summit%202015%20Flyer%20Invitation.pdf
--------------------------------------
We would greatly appreciate any assistance you may be able to provide with any type of notification of this "1st-of-its-kind" event to your subscribers of ProMED-mail and those that visit the ISID ProMED-mail website.

This event is hosted and sponsored by Florida Hospital for Children (Orlando, Florida) and presented by The Jordan Smelski Foundation for Amoeba Awareness and The Florida Department of Health in Seminole County, in partnership with The Florida Department of Health in Orange County.

This event is for: clinicians (FMA Accreditation Program AMA PRA Category 1 Credit is offered), researchers, and others involved in the prevention or treatment of infections with free-living amoeba and/or research in any area related to freshwater free-lining amoebae and the infections they cause.

There is no charge to attend the event. (RSVP for attending by calling (407)303-KIDS(5437)).

For those who are not able to attend, it will be available not only as a live stream webcast event (http://www.hospitalchurch.org/livestream) but also available for viewing for a period of time after the event.

There is no charge to view online nor is there a registration process needed to view the event online. At this time, no CME's are offered for viewing the webcast.

The Amoeba Summit will cover medical treatment, research issues, ecology, epidemiology, as well as a panel discussion to conclude the symposium.

Presenters will include:

- Dr. William Linam (Successful Treatment of an Adolescent with _Naegleria fowleri_ Primary Amebic Meningoencephalitis, W. Matthew Linam, et al, Pediatrics, Vol. 135, Number 3, March 2015);

- Francine Marciano-Cabral, Ph.D., Department of Microbiology and Immunology, Virginia Commonwealth University, Medical Center;

- Jennifer Cope, MD, MPH, Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, and others.

Please feel free to contact me if you have any questions.

--
Jack F. Tracy, M.Ed.
